**Imputation Approach for Handling Incomplete Datasets**

Our approach involves multiple imputations of incomplete datasets "m" times, followed by analysis of the "m" imputed datasets. The results from these analyses are then combined to produce a final outcome.

**Dataset Description**

Table 1 provides an overview of the datasets utilized in this study.

| Sr. No | Dataset | Description | No. of Instances | No. of Attributes |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Wine Dataset | Chemical analysis results from three different cultivars of wine grown in Italy | 178 | 13 |
| 2 | Glass Identification | Comparison test between BEAGLE, nearest-neighbor algorithm, and discriminant analysis for glass identification | 214 | 11 |
| 3 | Concrete Comprehensive Strength | Nonlinear function of age and ingredients affecting concrete compressive strength | 1030 | 9 |
| 4 | Indian Liver Patient Dataset | Patient records from north east of Andhra Pradesh, India (liver patients: 416, non-liver patients: 167) | 583 | 10 |
| 5 | Seeds Dataset | Geometrical properties measurements for three wheat varieties (Kama, Rosa, and Canadian) | - | 7 |

Note: The number of attributes for the Seeds Dataset has been corrected from 70 to 7.
